n [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/vadovicova-breaks-world-record-shooting-world-cup|title=Vadovicova breaks world record at shooting World Cup|publisher=IPC|date=15 March 2014|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IPC profile|surname=Vadovicova|givenname=Veronika}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vadovicova, Veronika}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Slovak female sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Paralympic shooters of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Paralympic medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Trnava]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Graham87", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronika_Vadovi%C4%8Dov%C3%A1"}
{"title_page": "S\u00e2nnicolau Mare", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|official_name                     = S\u00e2nnicolau Mare\n|image_map              = Sannicolau Mare jud Timis.png\n|image_skyline                     = Biserica Sarbeasca.jpg\n|image_caption                     = Serbian church\n|image_shield                      =\n|leader_name                       = D\u0103nu\u021b Groza<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party                      = PNL\n|area_total_km2                    = 136.77\n|coordinates                       = {{coord|46|4|20|N|20|37|46|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website                           = {{url|http://www.sannicolau-mare.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''S\u00e2nnicolau Mare''' (formerly spelled ''S\u00eennicolau Mare'', {{IPA-ro|s\u0268nniko\u02ccla.u \u02c8mare}}) is a town in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]] and the westernmost of the country. Located in the [[Banat]] region, along the borders with [[Serbia]] and [[Hungary]], it has a population of just under 12,000.\n\n==Name==\nIn [[German language|German]], it is known as ''Gro\u00df Sankt Nikolaus'', in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] as ''Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s'', in [[Banat Bulgarian language|Banat Bulgarian]] as ''Smiklu\u0161'', and in [[Serbian language|Serbian]] as \u0421\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0448 / ''Sent Nikola\u0161''. It is translated as \"Great St. Nicholas\" in English.\n\n==History==\n[[File:1895 NagySzMiklos 1kr Banat.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Kingdom of Hungary, cancelled at NAGY SZ-MIKLOS in 1895]]\n\n{{see also|Morisena (castra)}}\nNear S\u00e2nnicolau Mare there are the remains of Morisena, an ancient town, seat of Roman legions and of medieval dukes of Banat. After the [[Treaty of Passarowitz]] (1718) until 1918, S\u00e2nnicolau Mare (and the Banat) was part of the [[Austrian monarchy]], Temes District;<ref>Handbook of Austria and Lombardy-Venetia Cancellations on the Postage Stamp Issues 1850-1864, by Edwin MUELLER, 1961.</ref> in [[Transleithania]] after the [[compromise of 1867]] in [[Austria-Hungary]].\nIn the late 18th century, the [[Habsburg]] dynasty of Austria recruited German farmers and artisans to resettle areas along the [[Danube]] that had been depopulated during the Ottoman reign and the plague. They were allowed to keep their own religion, language and culture, and many German villages were founded in the [[Banat]]. The descendants of the ethnic Germans became known as [[Danube Swabians]] (''Donauschwaben'') and spoke a distinct form of German that became different from what evolved in the principal states. This is one reason for the high proportion of ethnic Germans in the town before [[World War II]]. After the war, many left the area to escape Soviet dominance; others were expelled because of anti-German sentiment throughout eastern Europe.\n\nThe town was a district center in [[Torontal County]] during [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] rule. The town served as the county seat between 1807 and 1820 due to a great fire in [[Zrenjanin|Gro\u00dfbetschkerek]], the county seat. Occupied by [[Serbia]]n troops in 1918 during [[World War I]], the town became part of Romania in 1919 during the realignment after the war.\n\nS\u00e2nnicolau Mare is known for the [[Treasure of Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s|Treasure of Nagy Szent Miklos]], a treasure of 23 gold objects discovered here in 1799 (it was then called ''Nagy Szent Miklos'' / ''Gro\u00df-Sankt-Niklaus'' in the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]). The pieces are on display in the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]] and the [[National Historical Museum (Bulgaria)|National Museum of History]], [[Sofia]]. The town is the birthplace of [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]], the great 20th-century Hungarian composer, and of Karoly Szenassy, the great Hungarian-Yugoslavian violinist. The town is 64 kilometers away from [[Timi\u0219oara]], the biggest city in the region.\n\n==Demographics==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Vedere-centrul.jpg]] -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: font-size:93%;width:300px;height:16;border:0px;text-align:left;line-height:120%;margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Historical population of S\u00e2nnicolau Mare'''<ref>[http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=3625 Erd\u00e9ly etnikai \u00e9s felekezeti statisztik\u00e1ja<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Romanians\n! Hungarians\n! Germans\n! Serbs\n! Bulgarians\n|-\n| 1880\n| 10,836 \n| 31.3%\n| 10.8%\n| 41.2%\n| 11.4%\n| N.D.\n|-\n| 1890\n| 12,311 \n| 31.3%\n| 12.2%\n| 43.5%\n| 10.3%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1900\n| 12,639 \n| 33.1%\n| 15.3%\n| 41.1%\n| 9.8%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1910\n| 12,357 \n| 32.6%\n| 17.5%\n| 39%\n| 9.2%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1920\n| 10,900 \n| 36.1%\n| 10.6%\n| 40.1%\n| N.D%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1930\n| 10,676 \n| 40%\n| 11.6%\n| 35.2%\n| 7.5%\n| 0.3%\n|-\n| 1941\n| 10,640 \n| 42.1%\n| 10.1%\n| 35%\n| N.D\n| N.D\n|-\n| 1956\n| 9,956 \n| 54.6%\n| 12.4%\n| 24.4%\n| 6.5%\n| 0.8%\n|- \n| 1966\n| 11,428 \n| 59.4%\n| 10.9%\n| 21.8%\n| 6.4%\n| 1%\n|- \n| 1977\n| 12,811 \n| 62.2%\n| 10.9%\n| 19%\n| 4.7%\n| 1.6%\n|- \n| 1992\n| 13,083\n| 73.4%\n| 10.6%\n| 5.9%\n| 4.6%\n| 3.1%\n|- \n| 2002<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant_loc.jsp?regiune_id=1832&judet_id=2057&localitate_id=2064 Recensamant 2001<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| 12,914\n| 76.8%\n| 9.4%\n| 3.2%\n| 3.6%\n| 3.6%\n|- \n| 2011\n| 12,312\n| 73.7%\n| 7.2%\n| 2.1%\n| 3.0%\n| 3.0%\n|}\n\nAt the 2011 census, the town counted 12,312 inhabitants: 73.7% Romanians, 7.2% Hungarians, 3.1% Roms, 3.0% Serbs, 3.0% Bulgarians, 2.1% Germans, 0.3% other and for 7.5% no ethnic information was available.<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab8. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 11 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Castelul_Nako.jpg|Nako Castle\nFile:Castelu_Nako_2.jpg|Nako Castle 2\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Treasure of Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|S\u00e2nnicolau Mare}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080712193918/http://www.cutiutza.nysart.ro/ Events in Sannicolau-Mare]\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sannicolau Mare}}\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n[[Category:Former Danube Swabian communities in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|official_name                     = S\u00e2nnicolau Mare\n|image_map              = Sannicolau Mare jud Timis.png\n|image_skyline                     = Biserica Sarbeasca.jpg\n|image_caption                     = Serbian church\n|image_shield                      =\n|leader_name                       = D\u0103nu\u021b Groza\n|leader_party                      = PNL\n|area_total_km2                    = 136.77\n|coordinates                       = {{coord|46|4|20|N|20|37|46|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website                           = {{url|http://www.sannicolau-mare.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''S\u00e2nnicolau Mare''' (formerly spelled ''S\u00eennicolau Mare'', {{IPA-ro|s\u0268nniko\u02ccla.u \u02c8mare}}) is a town in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]] and the westernmost of the country. Located in the [[Banat]] region, along the borders with [[Serbia]] and [[Hungary]], it has a population of just under 12,000.\n\n==Name==\nIn [[German language|German]], it is known as ''Gro\u00df Sankt Nikolaus'', in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] as ''Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s'', in [[Banat Bulgarian language|Banat Bulgarian]] as ''Smiklu\u0161'', and in [[Serbian language|Serbian]] as \u0421\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0448 / ''Sent Nikola\u0161''. It is translated as \"Great St. Nicholas\" in English.\n\n==History==\n[[File:1895 NagySzMiklos 1kr Banat.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Kingdom of Hungary, cancelled at NAGY SZ-MIKLOS in 1895]]\n\n{{see also|Morisena (castra)}}\nNear S\u00e2nnicolau Mare there are the remains of Morisena, an ancient town, seat of Roman legions and of medieval dukes of Banat. After the [[Treaty of Passarowitz]] (1718) until 1918, S\u00e2nnicolau Mare (and the Banat) was part of the [[Austrian monarchy]], Temes District;<ref>Handbook of Austria and Lombardy-Venetia Cancellations on the Postage Stamp Issues 1850-1864, by Edwin MUELLER, 1961.</ref> in [[Transleithania]] after the [[compromise of 1867]] in [[Austria-Hungary]].\nIn the late 18th century, the [[Habsburg]] dynasty of Austria recruited German farmers and artisans to resettle areas along the [[Danube]] that had been depopulated during the Ottoman reign and the plague. They were allowed to keep their own religion, language and culture, and many German villages were founded in the [[Banat]]. The descendants of the ethnic Germans became known as [[Danube Swabians]] (''Donauschwaben'') and spoke a distinct form of German that became different from what evolved in the principal states. This is one reason for the high proportion of ethnic Germans in the town before [[World War II]]. After the war, many left the area to escape Soviet dominance; others were expelled because of anti-German sentiment throughout eastern Europe.\n\nThe town was a district center in [[Torontal County]] during [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] rule. The town served as the county seat between 1807 and 1820 due to a great fire in [[Zrenjanin|Gro\u00dfbetschkerek]], the county seat. Occupied by [[Serbia]]n troops in 1918 during [[World War I]], the town became part of Romania in 1919 during the realignment after the war.\n\nS\u00e2nnicolau Mare is known for the [[Treasure of Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s|Treasure of Nagy Szent Miklos]], a treasure of 23 gold objects discovered here in 1799 (it was then called ''Nagy Szent Miklos'' / ''Gro\u00df-Sankt-Niklaus'' in the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]). The pieces are on display in the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]] and the [[National Historical Museum (Bulgaria)|National Museum of History]], [[Sofia]]. The town is the birthplace of [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]], the great 20th-century Hungarian composer, and of Karoly Szenassy, the great Hungarian-Yugoslavian violinist. The town is 64 kilometers away from [[Timi\u0219oara]], the biggest city in the region.\n\n==Demographics==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Vedere-centrul.jpg]] -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: font-size:93%;width:300px;height:16;border:0px;text-align:left;line-height:120%;margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Historical population of S\u00e2nnicolau Mare'''<ref>[http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=3625 Erd\u00e9ly etnikai \u00e9s felekezeti statisztik\u00e1ja<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Romanians\n! Hungarians\n! Germans\n! Serbs\n! Bulgarians\n|-\n| 1880\n| 10,836 \n| 31.3%\n| 10.8%\n| 41.2%\n| 11.4%\n| N.D.\n|-\n| 1890\n| 12,311 \n| 31.3%\n| 12.2%\n| 43.5%\n| 10.3%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1900\n| 12,639 \n| 33.1%\n| 15.3%\n| 41.1%\n| 9.8%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1910\n| 12,357 \n| 32.6%\n| 17.5%\n| 39%\n| 9.2%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1920\n| 10,900 \n| 36.1%\n| 10.6%\n| 40.1%\n| N.D%\n| N.D.\n|- \n| 1930\n| 10,676 \n| 40%\n| 11.6%\n| 35.2%\n| 7.5%\n| 0.3%\n|-\n| 1941\n| 10,640 \n| 42.1%\n| 10.1%\n| 35%\n| N.D\n| N.D\n|-\n| 1956\n| 9,956 \n| 54.6%\n| 12.4%\n| 24.4%\n| 6.5%\n| 0.8%\n|- \n| 1966\n| 11,428 \n| 59.4%\n| 10.9%\n| 21.8%\n| 6.4%\n| 1%\n|- \n| 1977\n| 12,811 \n| 62.2%\n| 10.9%\n| 19%\n| 4.7%\n| 1.6%\n|- \n| 1992\n| 13,083\n| 73.4%\n| 10.6%\n| 5.9%\n| 4.6%\n| 3.1%\n|- \n| 2002<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant_loc.jsp?regiune_id=1832&judet_id=2057&localitate_id=2064 Recensamant 2001<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| 12,914\n| 76.8%\n| 9.4%\n| 3.2%\n| 3.6%\n| 3.6%\n|- \n| 2011\n| 12,312\n| 73.7%\n| 7.2%\n| 2.1%\n| 3.0%\n| 3.0%\n|}\n\nAt the 2011 census, the town counted 12,312 inhabitants: 73.7% Romanians, 7.2% Hungarians, 3.1% Roms, 3.0% Serbs, 3.0% Bulgarians, 2.1% Germans, 0.3% other and for 7.5% no ethnic information was available.<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab8. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 11 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Castelul_Nako.jpg|Nako Castle\nFile:Castelu_Nako_2.jpg|Nako Castle 2\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Treasure of Nagyszentmikl\u00f3s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|S\u00e2nnicolau Mare}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080712193918/http://www.cutiutza.nysart.ro/ Events in Sannicolau-Mare]\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sannicolau Mare}}\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n[[Category:Former Danube Swabian communities in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A2nnicolau_Mare"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Del Ray", "text_new": "{{short description|American deceased professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name                 = Jimmy Del Ray\n| image                = Jimmy Del Ray (cropped).jpg\n| birth_name           = David Everett Ferrier<ref name=TBO/>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1962|11|30}}<ref name=OWOWDelRay/>\n| birth_place          = [[Grove City, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|2014|12|6|1962|11|30}}\n| death_place          = [[Tampa, Florida]], United States\n| death_cause          = [[Myocardial infarction]]\n| names                = Jimmy Backlund<ref name=PWIYears100/><br />Jimmy Del Ray<ref name=PWIYears100/><br />Jimmy Graffiti<br />Jumo Kenya\n| height               = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| weight               = {{convert|230|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| billed               =\n| trainer              = The Mighty Yankee\n| debut                = 1985<ref name=OWOWDelRay/><ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| retired              = 1997\n}}\n'''David Everett Ferrier''' (November 30, 1962 \u2013 December 6, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], better known by his [[ring name]], '''\"[[Gigolo]]\" Jimmy Del Ray'''. Del Ray was best known for his appearances in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) as one half of [[the Heavenly Bodies]] with his [[tag team]] partner, [[Tom Prichard]].<ref name=TBO>[http://tbo.com/news/breaking-news/single-vehicle-accident-on-us-301-kills-valrico-man-20141207/ \"Single vehicle accident on U.S. 301 kills Valrico man\", TBO.com staff]</ref><ref name=OWOWDelRay>{{cite web | url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/j/jimmy-del-ray/ | title=Jimmy Del Ray Profile | publisher=Online World of Wrestling | accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n{{see also|The Heavenly Bodies}}\nFerrier was trained by The Mighty Yankee and debuted in 1985 as \"Jimmy Richland\", which most thought was his real name. In the late 1980s, Del Ray joined [[Championship Wrestling from Florida]] as \"Jumo Kenya\". He later changed his ring name to \"Jimmy Backlund\" and formed a [[tag team]] with [[Brett Woyan|Brett Sawyer]] known as \"The Playboys\". The Playboys were awarded the vacant [[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship|FCW Tag Team Championship]] on July 1, 1989. They held the titles until August 22, when they were defeated by [[the Nasty Boys]].\n\nDel Ray later joined [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]] (SMW), where he replaced [[Stan Lane]] as one half of [[the Heavenly Bodies]] with [[Tom Prichard]].<ref name=PWIYears100/> He was given the name Jimmy Del Ray as a small on Lane, because Lane was billed during his career as being from [[Delray Beach, Florida]]. The Heavenly Bodies were [[Manager (professional wrestling)|managed]] by [[Jim Cornette|James E. Cornette]], and won the [[SMW Tag Team Championship]] on three occasions.<ref name=PWIYears100/><ref name=SMWTag/> Cornette put the \"Gigolo\" moniker on his name as a play off his physique. While Del Ray was an agile and able wrestler at the time, he had a slightly pudgy midsection that shook, or \"jiggled\" when he did a [[taunt]]ing dance.\n\nAlong with Cornette, the Heavenly Bodies debuted in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] in 1993. They made their first televised appearance on the August 9, 1993 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'', defeating Bobby Who and [[Mike Bucci]].<ref name=WWF9099Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 2: WWF 1990 - 1999  | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2013 | asin=B00RWUNSRS}}</ref> They made two more appearances on ''Raw'' that year; they were defeated by [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[The Steiner Brothers]] in a title match on August 30, and were victorious over Mark Thomas and Scott Taylor on August 4. At [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam 1993]] on August 30, the Heavenly Bodies faced the Steiner Brothers with the World Tag Team Championship on the line, but were defeated.<ref name=\"ss93\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#93|title=SummerSlam|work=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=December 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061913/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#93|archive-date=October 23, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Survivor Series (1993)|1993 Survivor Series]] on November 24 in the [[Boston Garden]], the Heavenly Bodies faced [[The Rock 'n' Roll Express]] for the [[SMW Tag Team Championship]]. Though the Rock 'N Roll Express appeared to have the match won, the Heavenly Bodies defeated them after Del Ray struck [[Robert Gibson (wrestler)|Robert Gibson]] with Cornette's [[Racquet|tennis racket]] while the referee was distracted, enabling Prichard to pin Gibson and win the titles.<ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X]] on March 20, 1994 in [[Madison Square Garden]], the Heavenly Bodies defeated [[The Bushwhackers]] in a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark match]].<ref name=wwf1994>{{cite web|title=1994|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/94.htm|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> They returned to WWF television on the April 25 episode of ''Raw'', defeating John Paul and Jason Headings. They made sporadic appearances on ''Raw'' over the next year, with their final appearance being a loss to [[The Smoking Gunns]] on the March 20, 1995 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> At the [[Survivor Series (1994)|1994 Survivor Series]] on November 23, the Heavenly Bodies took part in a ten-man survivor match, teaming with [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], [[Chris Chavis|Tatanka]], and [[King Kong Bundy]] as [[Ted DiBiase|Ted DiBiase's]] Million Dollar Team. The Million Dollar Team defeated their opponents, Guts and Glory ([[Lex Luger]], [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]], [[Bryan Clark|Adam Bomb]], and the Smoking Gunns), although both Prichard and Del Ray were eliminated from the match.<ref name=pwh>{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 1994|work=Pro Wrestling History | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/survivor.html#94|accessdate=2008-05-13}}</ref> Prichard and Del Ray both participated in the 30 man Royal Rumble match on January 22, 1995.<ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\nThe Heavenly Bodies made several appearances in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] in December 1995 as members of [[Raven's Nest#Extreme Championship Wrestling|Raven's Nest]]. At [[December to Dismember (1995)|ECW December To Dismember: Ultimate Jeopardy]] on December 9, the Heavenly Bodies faced [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven's]] enemies, the [[the Public Enemy (professional wrestling)|Public Enemy]], in a tag team bout. The match had stipulations applying to the losers - if the Public Enemy lost, they would face one another later that night, while if the Heavenly Bodies lost, [[the Eliminators]] (members of Raven's Nest) would be forced to leave ECW, while their manager, [[Jason Knight|Jason]], would have his head shaved. Moreover, if the Heavenly Bodies were defeated, then Raven's valet, [[Beulah McGillicutty]], would be forced to spend a week with [[Tommy Dreamer]], while Raven's Nest member [[Stevie Richards]] would be locked in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage]] for five minutes with the winners of the Ultimate Jeopardy match later that night. The Heavenly Bodies lost their match, leading to the enforcement of the aforementioned stipulations. Later that evening, Raven, Richards, the Eliminators, and the Heavenly Bodies faced Dreamer, [[the Pitbulls]], and the Public Enemy in an [[Professional wrestling match types#War games|ultimate jeopardy match]]. The match was won by Dreamer, who pinned Richards. Richards was subsequently locked in the cage with Dreamer's team, but Raven and his Nest attacked Dreamer's team before they could hurt him. Raven's Nest then attacked Dreamer's team until [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] drove them away.\n\nDel Ray later joined [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as Jimmy Graffiti.<ref name=WCW9501Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 5: World Championship Wrestling 1995-2001 | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2015 | isbn=1499656343}}</ref> He took part in the three ring [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] at the 1996 [[World War 3 (1996)|World War 3]] event on November 24. Del Ray remained in WCW until a knee injury forced him to retire in 1997. After retiring, he worked as an instructor in [[Steve Keirn|Steve Keirn's]] [[Florida|Floridian]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#School|professional wrestling school]] for several years,<ref name=OWOWDelRay/> training wrestlers such as [[Buck Quartermain]] and Steve Madison, and managed a tag team known as the New Heavenly Bodies. Del Ray later retired from training wrestlers and started a hardwood flooring company named Ferrier's Fine Flooring Inc. in Tampa, Florida in March 2006. In September 2013, he registered another Tampa company called Ferrier's Flooring Inc.\n\n==Death==\nFerrier, who lived in [[Valrico, Florida]], died at the [[Tampa General Hospital]] on December 6, 2014. He suffered a [[heart attack]] at the wheel of his truck on US 301 near the Florida State Fairgrounds. Two days later, WWE.com noted his death and offered condolences to his friends, family and colleagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52044-wwe-issues-statement-on-jimmy-del-ray-s-passing|title=WWE issues statement on Jimmy Del Ray's passing|date=December 8, 2014|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 9, 2014|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Championship Wrestling from Florida]]'''\n**[[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship|FCW Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Brett Sawyer]]<ref name=FloridaTag>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | chapter= Florida: FCW Tag Team TitleHeavyweight Title| isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''[[W*ING|Wrestling International New Generations]]'''\n**[[WWC World Junior Heavyweight Championship|W*ING World Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC World Junior Heavyweight Championship#title history|1 time]])<ref name=WingJr>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | chapter= Japan: W*ING Junior Heavyweight Title| isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''Florida Championship Wrestling / Pro Wrestling Federation'''\n**PWF Junior Heavyweight Championship (3 times)\n*'''Future Championship Wrestling'''\n**FCW Junior Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South]]'''\n**[[IWA Mid-South Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWA Mid-South Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''Pennsylvania Championship Wrestling'''\n**PCW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with [[Tom Prichard]]<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him '''73''' of the 100 best tag teams of the \"PWI Years\" with Tom Prichard in 2003<ref name=PWIYears100>{{cite news|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 100 Tag Teams of the PWI Years: 17 The Heavenly Bodies |work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Sports and Entertainment publications LLC|location=Blue Bell, [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]|id=November 2003|page=20|date=October 18, 2003}}</ref>\n*'''[[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]]'''\n**[[SMW Beat the Champ Television Championship]] ([[SMW Beat the Champ Television Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"SMWTag\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Knoxville: Smokey Mountain Wrestling Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n**[[SMW Tag Team Championship]] ([[SMW Tag Team Championship#Title history|3 times]]) \u2013 with Tom Prichard<ref name=\"SMWTag\"/>\n*'''[[Frontier Martial Arts Wrestling]]'''\n**[[AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship|FMW World Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Japan) FMW World Light Heavyweight Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[USWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[USWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with Tom Prichard<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Memphis: United States Wrestling Association Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1079964|name=Jimmy Del Ray}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Del Ray, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Grove City, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Valrico, Florida]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name                 = Jimmy Del Ray\n| image                = Jimmy Del Ray (cropped).jpg\n| birth_name           = David Everett Ferrier<ref name=TBO/>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1962|11|30}}<ref name=OWOWDelRay/>\n| birth_place          = [[Grove City, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|2014|12|6|1962|11|30}}\n| death_place          = [[Tampa, Florida]], United States\n| death_cause          = [[Myocardial infarction]]\n| names                = Jimmy Backlund<ref name=PWIYears100/><br />Jimmy Del Ray<ref name=PWIYears100/><br />Jimmy Graffiti<br />Jumo Kenya\n| height               = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| weight               = {{convert|230|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| billed               =\n| trainer              = The Mighty Yankee\n| debut                = 1985<ref name=OWOWDelRay/><ref name=PWIYears100/>\n| retired              = 1997\n}}\n'''David Everett Ferrier''' (November 30, 1962 \u2013 December 6, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], better known by his [[ring name]], '''\"[[Gigolo]]\" Jimmy Del Ray'''. Del Ray was best known for his appearances in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) as one half of [[the Heavenly Bodies]] with his [[tag team]] partner, [[Tom Prichard]].<ref name=TBO>[http://tbo.com/news/breaking-news/single-vehicle-accident-on-us-301-kills-valrico-man-20141207/ \"Single vehicle accident on U.S. 301 kills Valrico man\", TBO.com staff]</ref><ref name=OWOWDelRay>{{cite web | url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/j/jimmy-del-ray/ | title=Jimmy Del Ray Profile | publisher=Online World of Wrestling | accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n{{see also|The Heavenly Bodies}}\nFerrier was trained by The Mighty Yankee and debuted in 1985 as \"Jimmy Richland\", which most thought was his real name. In the late 1980s, Del Ray joined [[Championship Wrestling from Florida]] as \"Jumo Kenya\". He later changed his ring name to \"Jimmy Backlund\" and formed a [[tag team]] with [[Brett Woyan|Brett Sawyer]] known as \"The Playboys\". The Playboys were awarded the vacant [[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship|FCW Tag Team Championship]] on July 1, 1989. They held the titles until August 22, when they were defeated by [[the Nasty Boys]].\n\nDel Ray later joined [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]] (SMW), where he replaced [[Stan Lane]] as one half of [[the Heavenly Bodies]] with [[Tom Prichard]].<ref name=PWIYears100/> He was given the name Jimmy Del Ray as a small on Lane, because Lane was billed during his career as being from [[Delray Beach, Florida]]. The Heavenly Bodies were [[Manager (professional wrestling)|managed]] by [[Jim Cornette|James E. Cornette]], and won the [[SMW Tag Team Championship]] on three occasions.<ref name=PWIYears100/><ref name=SMWTag/> Cornette put the \"Gigolo\" moniker on his name as a play off his physique. While Del Ray was an agile and able wrestler at the time, he had a slightly pudgy midsection that shook, or \"jiggled\" when he did a [[taunt]]ing dance.\n\nAlong with Cornette, the Heavenly Bodies debuted in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] in 1993. They made their first televised appearance on the August 9, 1993 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'', defeating Bobby Who and [[Mike Bucci]].<ref name=WWF9099Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 2: WWF 1990 - 1999  | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2013 | asin=B00RWUNSRS}}</ref> They made two more appearances on ''Raw'' that year; they were defeated by [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Champions]] [[The Steiner Brothers]] in a title match on August 30, and were victorious over Mark Thomas and Scott Taylor on August 4. At [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam 1993]] on August 30, the Heavenly Bodies faced the Steiner Brothers with the World Tag Team Championship on the line, but were defeated.<ref name=\"ss93\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#93|title=SummerSlam|work=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=December 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061913/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#93|archive-date=October 23, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Survivor Series (1993)|1993 Survivor Series]] on November 24 in the [[Boston Garden]], the Heavenly Bodies faced [[The Rock 'n' Roll Express]] for the [[SMW Tag Team Championship]]. Though the Rock 'N Roll Express appeared to have the match won, the Heavenly Bodies defeated them after Del Ray struck [[Robert Gibson (wrestler)|Robert Gibson]] with Cornette's [[Racquet|tennis racket]] while the referee was distracted, enabling Prichard to pin Gibson and win the titles.<ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X]] on March 20, 1994 in [[Madison Square Garden]], the Heavenly Bodies defeated [[The Bushwhackers]] in a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark match]].<ref name=wwf1994>{{cite web|title=1994|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/94.htm|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> They returned to WWF television on the April 25 episode of ''Raw'', defeating John Paul and Jason Headings. They made sporadic appearances on ''Raw'' over the next year, with their final appearance being a loss to [[The Smoking Gunns]] on the March 20, 1995 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name=WWF9099Book/> At the [[Survivor Series (1994)|1994 Survivor Series]] on November 23, the Heavenly Bodies took part in a ten-man survivor match, teaming with [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], [[Chris Chavis|Tatanka]], and [[King Kong Bundy]] as [[Ted DiBiase|Ted DiBiase's]] Million Dollar Team. The Million Dollar Team defeated their opponents, Guts and Glory ([[Lex Luger]], [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]], [[Bryan Clark|Adam Bomb]], and the Smoking Gunns), although both Prichard and Del Ray were eliminated from the match.<ref name=pwh>{{cite web|title=Survivor Series 1994|work=Pro Wrestling History | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/survivor.html#94|accessdate=2008-05-13}}</ref> Prichard and Del Ray both participated in the 30 man Royal Rumble match on January 22, 1995.<ref name=WWF9099Book/>\n\nThe Heavenly Bodies made several appearances in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] in December 1995 as members of [[Raven's Nest#Extreme Championship Wrestling|Raven's Nest]]. At [[December to Dismember (1995)|ECW December To Dismember: Ultimate Jeopardy]] on December 9, the Heavenly Bodies faced [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven's]] enemies, the [[the Public Enemy (professional wrestling)|Public Enemy]], in a tag team bout. The match had stipulations applying to the losers - if the Public Enemy lost, they would face one another later that night, while if the Heavenly Bodies lost, [[the Eliminators]] (members of Raven's Nest) would be forced to leave ECW, while their manager, [[Jason Knight|Jason]], would have his head shaved. Moreover, if the Heavenly Bodies were defeated, then Raven's valet, [[Beulah McGillicutty]], would be forced to spend a week with [[Tommy Dreamer]], while Raven's Nest member [[Stevie Richards]] would be locked in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage]] for five minutes with the winners of the Ultimate Jeopardy match later that night. The Heavenly Bodies lost their match, leading to the enforcement of the aforementioned stipulations. Later that evening, Raven, Richards, the Eliminators, and the Heavenly Bodies faced Dreamer, [[the Pitbulls]], and the Public Enemy in an [[Professional wrestling match types#War games|ultimate jeopardy match]]. The match was won by Dreamer, who pinned Richards. Richards was subsequently locked in the cage with Dreamer's team, but Raven and his Nest attacked Dreamer's team before they could hurt him. Raven's Nest then attacked Dreamer's team until [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] drove them away.\n\nDel Ray later joined [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as Jimmy Graffiti.<ref name=WCW9501Book>{{cite book | first=Graham | last=Cawthon | title=the History of Professional Wrestling Vol 5: World Championship Wrestling 1995-2001 | publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform | year= 2015 | isbn=1499656343}}</ref> He took part in the three ring [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] at the 1996 [[World War 3 (1996)|World War 3]] event on November 24. Del Ray remained in WCW until a knee injury forced him to retire in 1997. After retiring, he worked as an instructor in [[Steve Keirn|Steve Keirn's]] [[Florida|Floridian]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#School|professional wrestling school]] for several years,<ref name=OWOWDelRay/> training wrestlers such as [[Buck Quartermain]] and Steve Madison, and managed a tag team known as the New Heavenly Bodies. Del Ray later retired from training wrestlers and started a hardwood flooring company named Ferrier's Fine Flooring Inc. in Tampa, Florida in March 2006. In September 2013, he registered another Tampa company called Ferrier's Flooring Inc.\n\n==Death==\nFerrier, who lived in [[Valrico, Florida]], died at the [[Tampa General Hospital]] on December 6, 2014. He suffered a [[heart attack]] at the wheel of his truck on US 301 near the Florida State Fairgrounds. Two days later, WWE.com noted his death and offered condolences to his friends, family and colleagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52044-wwe-issues-statement-on-jimmy-del-ray-s-passing|title=WWE issues statement on Jimmy Del Ray's passing|date=December 8, 2014|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 9, 2014|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Championship Wrestling from Florida]]'''\n**[[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship|FCW Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Brett Sawyer]]<ref name=FloridaTag>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | chapter= Florida: FCW Tag Team TitleHeavyweight Title| isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''[[W*ING|Wrestling International New Generations]]'''\n**[[WWC World Junior Heavyweight Championship|W*ING World Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC World Junior Heavyweight Championship#title history|1 time]])<ref name=WingJr>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | chapter= Japan: W*ING Junior Heavyweight Title| isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n*'''Florida Championship Wrestling / Pro Wrestling Federation'''\n**PWF Junior Heavyweight Championship (3 times)\n*'''Future Championship Wrestling'''\n**FCW Junior Heavyweight Championship (1 time)\n*'''[[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South]]'''\n**[[IWA Mid-South Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWA Mid-South Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''Pennsylvania Championship Wrestling'''\n**PCW Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with [[Tom Prichard]]<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him '''73''' of the 100 best tag teams of the \"PWI Years\" with Tom Prichard in 2003<ref name=PWIYears100>{{cite news|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 100 Tag Teams of the PWI Years: 17 The Heavenly Bodies |work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Sports and Entertainment publications LLC|location=Blue Bell, [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]|id=November 2003|page=20|date=October 18, 2003}}</ref>\n*'''[[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]]'''\n**[[SMW Beat the Champ Television Championship]] ([[SMW Beat the Champ Television Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"SMWTag\">{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Knoxville: Smokey Mountain Wrestling Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n**[[SMW Tag Team Championship]] ([[SMW Tag Team Championship#Title history|3 times]]) \u2013 with Tom Prichard<ref name=\"SMWTag\"/>\n*'''[[Frontier Martial Arts Wrestling]]'''\n**[[AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship|FMW World Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Japan) FMW World Light Heavyweight Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n*'''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[USWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[USWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with Tom Prichard<ref>{{cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2000|edition=4th |chapter= (Tennessee) Memphis: United States Wrestling Association Tag Team Title|isbn=0-9698161-5-4 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1079964|name=Jimmy Del Ray}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{AWA World Light Heavyweight Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Del Ray, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Grove City, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Valrico, Florida]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"American professional wrestler\" to \"American decease